@node "Requirements" "What you need to use it"

@{b}Requirements@{ub}
~~~~~~~~~~~~
  - An Amiga, CPU 68020 or better
  - OS 3.0 or better

@endnode


@node "Installation" "How to install it"

@{b}Installation@{ub}
~~~~~~~~~~~~
  Just copy the supplied files to any place you want.

  If you want SGrab to talk, ahm, write to you in another language
  than english, copy the appropriate catalog to

    LOCALE:Catalogs/whatever/

  or simply copy the complete Catalogs directory to SGrab's home
  directory so that it can find the catalog in its PROGDIR:Catalogs/...

  If you've just unpacked the original archive and do not intent to move
  the executable to another directory, SGrab is already prepared to
  find its Catalog.

  Currently there is a german, italian, norwegian, french, spanish and
  swedish translation.

@endnode


@node "Usage" "How to configure and use it"

@{b}Configuration and Usage@{ub}
~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
  You can run SGrab from Workbench or from a shell. For WB usage
  you'll have to specify options via tooltypes, otherwise you'll have to
  use commandline parameters.

  After you've started SGrab it'll wait a little letting you arrange
  what you want to grab (see below). When the time has passed it'll lock
  the screen and grab its image data. Finally the picture will be saved
  as normal ILBM or ILBM24, depending on the screen's depth.

  Starting with version 1.4 of SGrab a @{" graphical user interface " link "GUI"} is also
  available.

  Note that grabbing a big screen can take some seconds, so don't bother
  when graphical operations on that screen are frozen meanwhile.

  The following options are currently supported:

  @{" FILE           "  link "opt_file"}  Specify a filename
  @{" ICON           "  link "opt_icon"}  Define an icon template
  @{" CX_POPKEY      "  link "opt_popkey"}  Hotkey that tells SGrab to open its window
  @{" CX_POPUP       "  link "opt_popup"}  Open user interface when SGrab gets started
  @{" CX_PRIORITY    "  link "opt_priority"}  Priority of commodity handler
  @{" PUBSCREEN      "  link "opt_pubscreen"}  Name of pubscreen to open window on
  @{" CLIPUNIT       "  link "opt_clipunit"}  Save to clipboard 
  @{" NUMBER         "  link "opt_number"}  Number files all the way through
  @{" DELAY          "  link "opt_delay"}  Define time to wait before grabbing
  @{" WINDOW         "  link "opt_window"}  Grab a window, not a screen
  @{" WINDOWCONTENTS "  link "opt_windowcontents"}  Grab a window without its borders
  @{" MARK           "  link "opt_mark"}  Select area to grab using the mouse
  @{" VIEWER         "  link "opt_viewer"}  Specify an external viewer
  @{" CLIPVIEWER     "  link "opt_clipviewer"}  Specify an external viewer that can read from clipboard
  @{" WAITREFRESH    "  link "opt_waitrefresh"}  Wait some ticks to let the OS refresh the screen
  @{" AREXXPORT      "  link "opt_arexxport"}  Specify name of arexx port
  @{" NOBLIT         "  link "opt_noblit"}  Do not use the blitter to grab screens <= 8bit
  @{" CHECKDTMWRITE  "  link "opt_cdw"}  List only datatypes that support writing
  @{" DATATYPE       "  link "opt_datatype"}  Select datatype that should be used for saving  
  @{" JPG            "  link "opt_jpg"}  Save as jpeg
  @{" JPG_QUALITY    "  link "opt_jpg_quality"}  Set jpg quality
  @{" JPG_SMOOTHING  "  link "opt_jpg_smoothing"}  Set jpg smoothing factor 

@endnode


@node "opt_file" "FILE: Specify a filename"
@toc "Usage"

  @{b}FILE@{ub}
  ~~~~
    The name of file to write the ILBM to. It should include an absolute
    path, otherwise the file will be saved in SGrab's working
    directory (i.e. your current working directory if ran from a shell).

    The specified filename is not necessarily just a simple identifier
    representing exactly one disk object. Instead, it is a template which
    may contain keywords which will be replaced by their actual values
    whenever a screen or window is grabbed. Keywords are surrounded by
    braces, they are not case sensitive. For example

      FILE=sys:gfx/pic/cg_{size}_{number}.ilbm

    might become

      sys:gfx/pic/cg_1024x768x8_042.ilbm

    You can also think of "keywords" as "variables" or "macros", but as
    these kind of objects usually have characteristics (like being user
    definable) which are not true for SGrab's keywords I prefer to
    refer to them as "keywords".

    If the actual filename created this way should contain characters
    which are not valid for AmigaDOS filenames or which are conflicting
    with AmigaDOS pattern, those characters will be replaces by '_'s.
    Note that (especially when using keywords such as {title}) filenames
    may become too long for AmigaDOS. SGrab will truncate such
    filenames. Special care will be taken for the keyword {number} (see
    below). If the number of a file should "jut out" it will be shifted
    to the left forcing it to fit in.

    However, you might not be happy with shortened filenames as they tend
    to look ugly and an IYHO important part might be cut off. Thus,
    consider which parts of the filename you @{i}need @{ui}or just @{i}would like @{ui}to
    have and arrange the keywords as appropriate.

    Another way to shorten a filename is to limit the number of words a
    keyword can be expanded to. This is done by specifying

      {n:keyword}

    where n is the maximum number of words which will replace the
    keyword. For example {2:title} means "take the first two words of
    the title". Note that this notation is allowed for any keyword,
    however, (unless n equals 0) it will only affect some of them
    (because not all consist of multiple words), namely these are {title}
    and {owner}. Also note that SGrab might have a different idea of
    what a word is than what you might have expected... The only thing we
    all surely agree to accept as word separator is a blank -- however
    this won't be enough for practical cases (consider
    "foo:bar/baz.stuff" as title of an editor's Window, for example).
    Thus the definition of the set of word separators is necessarily
    based on guesses.

    The following keywords are currently supported

    @{" NUMBER "  link "kw_number"}
    @{" WIDTH  "  link "kw_width"}
    @{" HEIGHT "  link "kw_height"}
    @{" DEPTH  "  link "kw_depth"}
    @{" SIZE   "  link "kw_size"}
    @{" TITLE  "  link "kw_title"}
    @{" OWNER  "  link "kw_owner"}
    @{" TYPE   "  link "kw_type"}

  See also: @{" NUMBER " link "opt_number"}

@endnode

@node "kw_number" "NUMBER: Number files all the way through"
@toc "opt_file"

  @{b}{number}@{ub} will be replaced by the next greatest number if
  another file with (except for the number) the same filename does
  already exist.

  Say, for example, you specified  FILE=sys:gfx/cg_{number}.ilbm and
  `list sys:gfx`  shows

    cg_001.ilbm
    cg_030.ilbm
    cg_041.ilbm

  Then the created file will be named sys:gfx/cg_042.ilbm.

  Note that SGrab needs a way to determine the end of a number in an
  actual filename, thus you should not put digits (or keywords which are
  replaced by a sequence of digits) directly after {number}. For example
  FILE=sys:gfx/cg_{number}{depth}.ilbm  would not have been a good idea
  in the example above. SGrab will always interpret the largest
  sequence of digits found in an actual filename (starting at {number} in
  the filename template) as the number of the file.

  A number must be unique, thus, it is not possible to put multiple
  {number}s in the filename template.

  See also: Option @{" NUMBER " link "opt_number"}

@endnode


@node "kw_width" "WIDTH: The width of a screen of window"
@toc "opt_file"

  @{b}{width}@{ub} will be replaced by the width of the screen or window
  in pixels.

  See also: @{" HEIGHT " link "kw_height"} @{" DEPTH " link "kw_depth"} @{" SIZE " link "kw_size"}

@endnode


@node "kw_height" "HEIGHT: The height of a screen of window"
@toc "opt_file"

  @{b}{height}@{ub} will be replaced by the height of the screen or
  window in pixels.

  See also: @{" WIDTH " link "kw_width"} @{" DEPTH " link "kw_depth"} @{" SIZE " link "kw_size"}

@endnode


@node "kw_depth" "DEPTH: The depth of a screen"
@toc "opt_file"

  @{b}{depth}@{ub} will be replaced by the depth of the screen.

  See also: @{" WIDTH " link "kw_width"} @{" HEIGHT " link "kw_height"} @{" SIZE " link "kw_size"}

@endnode


@node "kw_size" "SIZE The size of a screen of window"
@toc "opt_file"

  @{b}{size}@{ub} will be replaced by the size of the screen or window in
  pixels. This is exactly the same as {width}x{height}x{depth}.

  See also: @{" WIDTH " link "kw_width"} @{" HEIGHT " link "kw_height"} @{" DEPTH " link "kw_depth"}

@endnode


@node "kw_title" "TITLE: The title of a screen of window"
@toc "opt_file"

  @{b}{title}@{ub} will be replaced by the title of the screen or window.
  If the object in question is untitled it will be named "unnamed".

  See also: @{" OWNER " link "kw_owner"}

@endnode


@node "kw_owner" "OWNER: The owner of a screen of window"
@toc "opt_file"

  @{b}{owner}@{ub} will be replaced by the owner of the screen or window.

  Note: It is not always possible to determine the owner of a screen or
  window.
  If the window is just used for output (i.e. does not have gadgets, a
  Close-Button, etc.) there is no way to figure out who has opened the
  window. Technically speaking: A window needs to have a UserPort to be
  able to determine its owner.

  A screen does actually never have owner. Thus {owner} might not be
  particularly useful when grabbing screens. SGrab will however try
  to find a somehow sensible name for {owner} even when used with a
  screen: It will look for a window on the screen and refer its owner as
  owner of the screen.

  If the owner cannot be determined {owner} will become "unknown".

  See also: @{" TITLE " link "kw_title"}

@endnode

@node "kw_type" "TYPE: "
@toc "opt_file"

  @{b}{type}@{ub} will be replaced by the filetype. If you don't use a datatype
  for saving, this will be ILBM. Otherwise the id of the dataype.

@endnode

@node "opt_icon" "ICON: Define an icon template"
@toc "Usage"

  @{b}ICON/K@{ub}
  ~~~~~~
    If you want an icon to be created for the FILE you can specify a
    template-icon using this parameter. This icon can contain tooltypes
    and a default tool you want to be invoked when you click on the icon.
    A sample icon named "Template" is supplied with this package. By
    default SGrab doesn't create icons.

  See also: @{" FILE " link "opt_file"}

@endnode

@node "opt_popkey" "CX_POPKEY: Hotkey that tells SGrab to open its window"
@toc "Usage"

  @{b}CX_POPKEY/K@{ub}
  ~~~~~~~~~~~
    This is the hotkey, the input sequence which opens the window if it is closed
    or brings it to the front if it is already open. You MUST specify this option
    if you want to use the @{" gui " link "GUI"}.

@endnode

@node "opt_popup" "CX_POPUP: Open user interface when sgrab gets started"
@toc "Usage"

  @{b}CX_POPUP/T@{ub}
  ~~~~~~~~~~
    This one tells SGrab to open its window when it is run for the first time. You
    must specify @{" CX_POPKEY " link "opt_popkey"} to make this option work.

@endnode

@node "opt_priority" "CX_PRIORITY: Priority of commodity handler"
@toc "Usage"

  @{b}CX_PRIORITY/K/N@{ub}
  ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
    Priority of commodity handler. Normally, you won't have to change this. 

@endnode

@node "opt_pubscreen" "PUBSCREEN: Screen to open the window on"
@toc "Usage"

  @{b}PUBSCREEN/K@{ub}
  ~~~~~~~~~~~
    Name of public screen to open window on. If not specified the default
    public screen is used.

@endnode

@node "opt_clipunit" "CLIPUNIT: Clipboard unit to save image data to"
@toc "Usage"

  @{b}CLIPUNIT/N/K@{ub}
  ~~~~~~~~~~~~  
    If you specify CLIPUNIT SGrab will save the screenshot to the given
    clipboard unit (eg. CLIPUNIT=0). NOTE: datatypes.lib always saves to
    to the primary unit.

@endnode

@node "opt_number" "NUMBER: Number files all the way through"
@toc "Usage"

  @{b}NUMBER/S@{ub}
  ~~~~~~~~
    Usually SGrab will save the picture in the file specified by the
    FILE option, thereby probably overwriting an existing file. With this
    option however, generated files will be numbered all the way through.
    I.e. the file actually created will be named <FILE>.<n> where <n> is
    the next greatest number of any already existing files matching
    "<FILE>.#[0-9]".

    This option is ignored if you do not specify the FILE option in which
    case a file-requester will be opened.

    See the docs to the keywords in the FILE option for a more flexible
    way to number files.

  See also: @{" FILE " link "opt_file"}

@endnode


@node "opt_delay" "DELAY: Define time to wait before grabbing"
@toc "Usage"

  @{b}DELAY/K/N@{ub}
  ~~~~~~~~~
    Number of seconds to wait before start grabbing.
    Default: 5.

@endnode


@node "opt_window" "WINDOW: Grab a window, not a screen"
@toc "Usage"

  @{b}WINDOW/S@{ub}
  ~~~~~~~~
    Usually SGrab grabs the frontmost screen. If you specify this
    option the currently activated window will be grabbed instead.

    NOTE: The operating system provides several types of windows
    (refresh-types, to be more precise) and not all of them can be
    grabbed if they are obscured. Actually, only a few can. Thus, you
    should make sure that the window you wanna grab is completely
    visible. If a part of a window cannot be grabbed because it is hidden
    it'll most probably be colored in background color or be garbled. An
    easy way to ensure "grabability" is to move the window in front of
    all other windows before running SGrab.

    ALSO NOTE: An applications can prevent SGrab from reading its
    window. Only very few do, though. Actually, I don't know any :-) If
    an application installs custom ClipRects you'll notice the same
    behavior as if a part of the window was obscured.

  See also: @{" WINDOWCONTENTS " link "opt_windowcontents"}

@endnode


@node "opt_windowcontents" "WINDOWCONTENTS: Grab a window without its borders"
@toc "Usage"

  @{b}WINDOWCONTENTS/S@{ub}
  ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
    This option implies WINDOW but does not grab the window's borders.

    NOTE: The operating system provides special windows, called
    "GimmeZeroZero" which "hide" their borders. SGrab can detect such
    windows and will always use WINDOWCONTENTS for them, even if you
    don't explicitly specify this option.

  See also: @{" WINDOW " link "opt_window"}

@endnode

@node "opt_mark" "MARK: Select area to grab using the mouse"
@toc "Usage"

  @{b}MARK/S@{ub}
  ~~~~~~
    Allows you to select which part of the screen should be grabbed. When 
    SGrab changes the mouse-pointer to a cross, move the mouse pointer to 
    the starting point, hold down the lmb, move to the ending point and 
    release the button.

@endnode

@node "opt_viewer" "VIEWER: Specify an external viewer"
@toc "Usage"

  @{b}VIEWER/K@{ub}
  ~~~~~~~~
    Viewer to use when you click on the "View" gadget. See also @{" GUI " link "gui"}.
    Default: SYS:Utilities/MultiView "%s"
    The %s will be replaced by the filename. IMPORTANT: If you specify your 
    own viewer you should use *"%s*" instead of %s!

@endnode

@node "opt_clipviewer" "CLIPVIEWER: Specify an external viewer that can read from clipboard"
@toc "Usage"

  @{b}CLIPVIEWER/K@{ub}
  ~~~~~~~~~~~~
    Same as @{" VIEWER " link "opt_viewer"}, but this one should be able to read from clipboard.
    See also @{" GUI " link "gui"}. Default: SYS:Utilities/MultiView CLIPBOARD CLIPUNIT %ld
    The %ld will be replaced by the clipunit specified via @{" CLIPUNIT " link "opt_clipunit"}.

@endnode

@node "opt_waitrefresh" "WAITREFRESH: Wait some ticks to let the OS refresh the screen"
@toc "Usage"

  @{b}WAITREFRESH/N/K@{ub}
  ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
    This option only takes effect when you use the @{" GUI " link "GUI"}!
    SGrab automatically closes its gui when you grab the current screen. In 
    order to allow the system to refresh the underlying parts of the screen,
    SGrab waits some ticks (1 tick = 1/50 sec) before it starts grabbing.
    WAITREFRESH can be used to change the size of this time gap, eg. if you
    have a slow system you may wish to enlarge it. Default: 25 ticks.

@endnode

@node "opt_arexxport" "AREXXPORT: Specify name of arexx port"
@toc "Usage"

  @{b}AREXXPORT/K@{ub}
  ~~~~~~~~~~~
    Allows you to change the name of the arexxport. Default: SGRAB

  See also @{" Arexx commands " link "arexxcoms"}.

@endnode

@node "opt_noblit" "NOBLIT: Don't use the blitter to grab screens <= 8bit"
@toc "Usage"

  @{b}NOBLIT/S@{ub}
  ~~~~~~~~
    This option has been introduced to fix a deadlock problem when MCX is used.
    Setting this option avoids the @{" deadlock " link "Bugs"} but slows down the grabbing
    process of planar screens. With a gfx-board you may gain some speed when
    this option is used.

@endnode

@node "opt_datatype" "DATATYPE: Select datatype that should be used for saving"
@toc "Usage"

  @{b}DATATYPE/K@{ub}
  ~~~~~~~~~~
    This option allows you to specify a datatype that should be used for saving.
    By default the internal ILBM encoder is used. DATATYPE also changes the
    initial state of the @{" filetype gadget " link "GUI"}.
    NOTE: You can only save ilbm pictures to the clipboard.

@endnode

@node "opt_cdw" "CHECKDTMWRITE: List only datatypes that support writing"
@toc "Usage"

  @{b}CHECKDTMWRITE/S@{ub}
  ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
    By default the @{" filetype gadget " link "GUI"} shows all (picture) datatypes that
    are currently available, no matter if they support writing imagedata in 
    their local format or not. Setting this option forces SGrab to list only
    those datatypes that support writing, for this purpose all datatypes must
    be loaded into memory and thus delays poping up the window.

@endnode

@node "opt_jpg" "JPG: save as jpeg"
@toc "Usage"

  @{b}JPG/K@{ub}
  ~~~~~
    If you don't specify @{" DATATYPE " link "opt_datatype"}, SGrab will save the imagedata as
    IFF-ILBM. When setting JPG the image will be saved as jpeg instead. JPG
    also changes the initial state of the @{" filetype gadget " link "GUI"}.
    NOTE: SGrab requires jpeg.library by Paul Huxham (util/libs/jpeglibrary*.
    lha). You can find the latest version of this library on Pauls homepage
    at http://mafeking.scouts.org.au/~paulh/.

  See also: @{" JPG_QUALITY " link "opt_jpg_quality}, @{" JPG_SMOOTHING " link "opt_jpg_smoothing}.

@endnode

@node "opt_jpg_quality" "JPG: Set jpeg quality"
@toc "Usage"

  @{b}JPG_QUALITY/K@{ub}
  ~~~~~~~~~~~~~
    This option allows to change the quality of the jpeg image to create.
    Default: 85 (Range: 1% - 100%)

  See also: @{" JPG " link "opt_jpg}, @{" JPG_SMOOTHING " link "opt_jpg_smoothing}.

@endnode

@node "opt_jpg_smoothing" "JPG: Set jpeg smoothing factor"
@toc "Usage"

  @{b}JPG_SMOOTHING/K@{ub}
  ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
    This option allows to change the smoothing factor of the jpeg image to 
    create. Default: 0 = no smoothing (Range: 0% - 100%)

  See also: @{" JPG " link "opt_jpg}, @{" JPG_QUALITY " link "opt_jpg_quality}.

@endnode

@node "GUI" "Graphical User Interface"
@toc "Usage"

  @{b}HOW IT WORKS@{ub}
  ~~~~~~~~~~~~
    Whenever you start SGrab with @{" CX_POPKEY " link "opt_popkey"} given, SGrab will install itself 
    as a commodity into the system. Each time you press the specified input 
    sequence, SGrab will open its GUI on the screen specified by the @{" PUBSCREEN " link "opt_pubscreen"} 
    option (screen and window will be brought to front if already open).

  @{b}THE GADGETS@{ub}
  ~~~~~~~~~~~
    Screens / Windows: This one shows all windows and screens currently
    available. The highlighted entries are the screens. You can use the 
    CRSR UP/DN keys to select an entry via the keyboard. If you have 
    notifyintuition.library by H.W.Schober installed the gadget will be 
    automatically updated each time when a window/screen is opened or closed.
    For windows that don't have a title, their coordinates and dimensions
    are shown instead.
 
    Windows: Turns on / off the displaying of windows in the "Screens / Windows" 
    gadget. The initial state of this gadget can be controlled by the @{" WINDOW " link "opt_window"}
    option.

    WINDOWCONTENTS: See @{" WINDOWCONTENTS " link "opt_windowcontents}.

    Grab: Grabs the selected screen / window.

    Mark & Grab: Pops the selected screen to the front and allows you to select
    the area to grab. See also @{" MARK " link "opt_mark"}.

    View: Views the last grab by using an external viewer. See also @{" VIEWER " link "opt_viewer"},
    @{" CLIPVIEWER " link "opt_clipviewer"}.

    slider gadget: Allows you to specify the time (in seconds) before SGrab
    actually starts a grab operation. See also @{" DELAY " link "opt_delay"}.
    You can use CRSR left / right to control this gadget via the keyboard.
    
    File: Where to save the imagedata to. See also @{" FILE " link "opt_file"}.

    Clipboard: Save imagedata to the clipboard unit specified by @{" CLIPUNIT " link "opt_clipunit"} 
    (0 by default).

    Filetype: Here you can select the datatype that should be used to save the
    imagedata. If you select 'ILBM (internal)', SGrabs' internal saver will be
    used. Using the internal saver is fastest way to grab a screen and requires
    less memory than datatypes. NOTE: Only a few datatypes support saving.
    See also: @{" DATATYPE " link "opt_datatype"}, @{" CHECKDTMWRITE " link "opt_cdw"}.
    
    The following two gadgets are only shown when jpeg.library is installed and
    'jpeg (internal)' of Filetypes gadget is chosen.

    JPEG Quality: See @{" JPG_QUALITY "  link "opt_jpg_quality"}.
    JPEG Smoothing: See @{" JPG_SMOOTHING "  link "opt_jpg_smoothing"}.


  @{b}THE MENU@{ub}
  ~~~~~~~~
    The menu only contains the standard menu items "About", "Hide" and "Quit"
    so I don't think I have to explain them to you :)

@endnode

@node "ARexx" "The ARexx Interface"
@toc "Usage"

  @{b}ARexx@{ub}
  ~~~~~~
    To use the arexx interface you must have easyrexx.library by Ketil Hunn
    installed (dev/misc/easyrexx.lha). Currently the following commands are
    available (most of them are similar to the wb/shell options):

    GRABSCREEN FILE,CLIPBOARD/S,SCREEN/K,DELAY/N/K,DESTDT=DATATYPE/K,JPG/S,Q=JPG_QUALITY/N/K,S=JPG_SMOOTHING/N/K,MARK/S
    GRABWINDOW FILE,CLIPBOARD/S,WINDOW/K,DELAY/N/K,WINDOWCONTENTS=WINC/S,DESTDT=DATATYPE/K,JPG/S,Q=JPG_QUALITY/N/K,S=JPG_SMOOTHING/N/K

     FILE: See @{" FILE " link "opt_file"}.
     CLIPBOARD: save to clipboard.
     SCREEN: Screen that should be grabbed identified by its title. You don't
     need to give the whole title. If you don't specify SCREEN the current 
     screen will be grabbed.
     WINDOW: Grab the window identified by its title. See also SCREEN.
     WINDOWCONTENTS: Don't grab the window borders. See also @{" WINDOWCONTENTS " link "opt_windowcontents"}.
     DATATYPE: See @{" DATATYPE " link "opt_datatype"}.
     DELAY: See @{" DELAY " link "opt_delay"}.
     JPG: See @{" JPG "  link "opt_jpg"}
     JPG_QUALITY: See @{" JPG_QUALITY "  link "opt_jpg_quality"}
     JPG_SMOOTHING: See @{" JPG_SMOOTHING "  link "opt_jpg_smoothing"}
     MARK: See @{" MARK "  link "opt_mark"}

    QUITSGRAB

     Guess what this option does ;)

    NOTE: You need to invoke SGrab with @{" CX_POPKEY " link "opt_popkey"} given in order to use
    the interface.

@endnode

@node "Diffs" "Differences between SGrab and CyberGrab"
@toc "SGrab vs. CyberGrab"

  @{b}Differences@{ub}
  ~~~~~~~~~~~
    ° sgrab has a GUI
    ° option SPAREMEM not supported - does anybody need it?
    ° option WINDOWFRAME not available, SGrab automatically uses
      WINDOWFRAME whenever possible.
    ° grabs planar screens faster
    ° clipboard support
    ° datatypes can be used
    ° ...

@endnode

@node "History" "How did it grow up"

  @{b}History@{ub}
  ~~~~~~~
  1.0   first public release
  1.1	crashed when grabbing large screen (compiler used 16bit math
	instead of 32bit ones).
  1.2	italian catalog by Nicola Pagani, norwegian catalog
	by Kimme Utsi, fixed stripes problem when grabbing
	< 8bit cgfx screens (only when SAVEMEM wasn't activated)
	<juergen urbanek>, added commodity support <freejack>,
	supports clipboard now
  1.3	for unknown reasons grabbing didn't work correctly on at least
	one computer (MARK and WINDOW) when using a friend bitmap (friend
	bitmaps were only used for native screens) <Henning `Faroul' Peters>,
	new mouse pointer image when using MARK
  1.4	finally sgrab got a gui, wbmsg wasn't replied, sometimes crashed the
	system when {Owner} / {Title} were used, flashes the screen when 
	grabbing has been done.
  1.5	{NUMBER} was broken when using the GUI. Reopens the window when it
	was closed before a grab. <Raphael Pilarczyk>
	french catalog by Didier Giron
  1.6	fixed a bug (not a real one, just a side-effect when using MCP or
	something similar) where the MARK operation seemed to "hang". Added
	a function to start an external viewer. DELAY is available from the 
	gui now. MARK can be aborted by pressing the rmb. Some minor 
	improvements. Finally, with help of Raphael Pilarczyk I found out
	why SGrab deadlocked Raphaels' machine, still not fixed :(. See 
	"Known bugs" for more.
  1.7b	missing swedish catalog by F. Söderberg is now available. By request
	of a SINGLE user I implemented an arexx interface. New NOBLIT option
	fixes problems with MCX and speeds up grabbing of <= 8bit screens
	when a gfxboard is installed. datatypes can be used for saving image
	data.
  1.7	Added support for jpeg.library by Paul Huxham. Removed arexx command
	MARKNGRAB, GRABSCREEN has a MARK option now. Some internal changes
	and bugfixes.

@endnode

@node "Future" "How it will grow up"

  @{b}Future@{ub}
  ~~~~~~
  ° new gui (using MUI, or something similiar)
  ° internal picture viewer
  ° bugfixes ;)
  ° your suggestions

@endnode

@node "Bugs" "Known bugs"

  @{b}Bugs@{ub}
  ~~~~
  MCX: The titleclock of this program does not lock the barlayer before it
       writes to the titlebar. This leads to deadlocks when SGrab tries to
       lock the screen. The @{" NOBLIT " link "opt_noblit"} Option of SGrab may help to avoid this
       problem.


@endnode

